Pelvic organ prolapse occurs when tissue supporting the pelvic organs – including the womb – becomes weak . 
  Complications include an uncomfortable dragging or ‘full’ feeling during sex . 
  Many women are offered a hysterectomy as a solution to the problem . 
  But a keyhole procedure uses an implanted mesh ‘sling’ to lift and hold the womb back in place and preserve fertility . 
  The procedure is called a sacrohysteropexy and is rare . 
  Just 1,072 admissions for the surgery in the past three years . 
 